title: For Sale:  VZ 2008 7.62x39
postcontent:
Up for sale is a VZ 2008 with a US made receiver and barrel. Comes with one mag and rifle is in like new condition. Its 100% reliable. 
This rifle is based off of a Czechoslovakian Vz. 58, has a milled receiver and looks similar to an AK47.
During the Cold War, the Soviets allowed the Czechs (unlike other Warsaw countries) to design their own rifle instead of forced adoption of the AK- as the Czechs have a long history of small arms design and innovation, thus creating the VZ58.
However, this rifle being designed about 10 yrs after the AK and has some advantages.
Including a shorter and lighter weight milled receiver, a simpler striker fire trigger, last round bolt hold open, slightly less recoil due to short stroke gas piston and the bolt has less mass than an AK. The total weight unloaded w/ mag is 6-1/2 lbs. The furniture is similar to mil surplus bakelite.
The VZ2008 are no longer being made; the original Czech rifles are still being imported in small numbers and go for $1k+. Plenty of after market parts are available to customize, if desired.
I'm looking for cash only. I may trade for an AK47, or possibly something unique.
Send me an email and I'll respond in 24 hrs or less.

postcontent:
I am selling a BARELY USED (less than 200 loads) Harrell's Precision Premuim Powder Measuer with the aluminum adjustable stand. I bought this last April, but never really got to use it much. Now, I dont have the time, or resources to reload as much as I would like. This is the most accurate, and consistent powder measure on the market. Of the 200 loads I did, after I each load, I would weigh the powder to verify. 95% of those were on the dot, the other 5% were maybe +/- 0.1 grains. You can't ask for anything better!
 
I first found out about this measurer at a competition in Texas. A guy had his stand set up hand making custom ammo on the spot. I talked to him about it, he showed me how accurate and consistent it was. He despensed 10 45.5 grain loads into little cups. He then weighed each one (without the cup of course) and all 10 were exactly 45.5 grains. I was sold! I sure couldn't do 10 like that with my RCBS powder measure
 
Here is the website info about the measure:
 
Our new PREMIUM Culver type measure is the finest measure we have ever made. It has two precision roller bearings, one on each end of the metering device, to reduce vertical play to a few ten thousandths of an inch. They also make it incredibly smooth, for a much better feel.
 
OTHER NEW FEATURES:⦁ Left or right hand use ⦁ Four cutting edges, two left and two right hand ⦁ Brass metering device encapsulated in a stainless steel bushing ⦁ New space saving design with 16 ounce bottle ⦁ 120 grain, 200 click, 6 clicks between numbers, .1 grain per click adjustment, easily converts to 4 clicksAlso included, is the Harrell's Powder Measure Stand. This has adjustable height, and clamp distance, so it can be mounted exactly where, and how you want it.

This sale will include the Powder Measure, 2 dispencer tubes (for small and large loads), the brass collar for attaching the tubes, the 16 oz powder bottle (I am missing the plastic stopper that goes in the top, but I will either find it, or something to replace it), and the aluminum stand (black).
